column8: Order

column6:
Definition:The geographical origin of the sample as defined by latitude and longitude. The values should be reported in decimal degrees and in WGS84 system
Structured comment name:lat_lon
Section:environment
Expected value:decimal degrees

Definition:The geographical origin of the sample as defined by the country or sea name followed by specific region name. Country or sea names should be chosen from the INSDC country list (http://insdc.org/country.html), or the GAZ ontology (v 1.512) (http://purl.bioontology.org/ontology/GAZ)
Structured comment name:geo_loc_name
Section:environment
Expected value:country or sea name (INSDC or GAZ):region(GAZ):specific location name

Definition:The time of sampling, either as an instance (single point in time) or interval. In case no exact time is available, the date/time can be right truncated i.e. all of these are valid times: 2008-01-23T19:23:10+00:00; 2008-01-23T19:23:10; 2008-01-23; 2008-01; 2008; Except: 2008-01; 2008 all are ISO8601 compliant
Structured comment name:collection_date
Section:environment
Expected value:date and time

Definition:Biomes are defined based on factors such as plant structures, leaf types, plant spacing, and other factors like climate. Biome should be treated as the descriptor of the broad ecological context of a sample. Examples include: desert, taiga, deciduous woodland, or coral reef. EnvO (v 2013-06-14) terms can be found via the link: www.environmentontology.org/Browse-EnvO
Structured comment name:env_biome
Section:environment
Expected value:EnvO

Definition:Environmental feature level includes geographic environmental features. Compared to biome, feature is a descriptor of the more local environment. Examples include: harbor, cliff, or lake. EnvO (v 2013-06-14) terms can be found via the link: www.environmentontology.org/Browse-EnvO
Structured comment name:env_feature
Section:environment
Expected value:EnvO

Definition:The environmental material level refers to the material that was displaced by the sample, or material in which a sample was embedded, prior to the sampling event. Environmental material terms are generally mass nouns. Examples include: air, soil, or water. EnvO (v 2013-06-14) terms can be found via the link: www.environmentontology.org/Browse-EnvO
Structured comment name:env_material
Section:environment
Expected value:EnvO

Definition:MIGS/MIMS/MIMARKS extension for reporting of measurements and observations obtained from one or more of the environments where the sample was obtained. All environmental packages listed here are further defined in separate subtables. By giving the name of the environmental package, a selection of fields can be made from the subtables and can be reported
Structured comment name:env_package
Section:migs/mims/mimarks extension
Expected value:CV

Definition:primary publication if isolated before genome publication; otherwise, primary genome report
Structured comment name:ref_biomaterial
Section:nucleic acid sequence source
Expected value:PMID, DOI or URL

Definition:Publication reference in the form of pubmed ID (pmid), digital object identifier (doi) or url for isolation and growth condition specifications of the organism/material
Structured comment name:isol_growth_condt
Section:nucleic acid sequence source
Expected value:PMID, DOI or URL

Definition:Sequencing method used; e.g. Sanger, pyrosequencing, ABI-solid
Structured comment name:seq_meth
Section:sequencing
Expected value:

Definition:How was the assembly done (e.g. with a text based assembler like phrap or a flowgram assembler); estimated error rate associated with the finished sequences (e.g. error rate of 1 in 1000 bp); and the method of calculation
Structured comment name:assembly
Section:sequencing
Expected value:assembly method; estimated error rate; method of calculation

Definition:Name/version of the assembly provided by the submitter that is used in the genome browsers and in the community
Structured comment name:assembly_name
Section:sequencing
Expected value:name and version of assemby

Definition:Was the genome project intended to produce a complete or draft genome, Coverage, the fold coverage of the sequencing expressed as 2x, 3x, 18x etc, and how many contigs were produced for the genome
Structured comment name:finishing_strategy
Section:sequencing
Expected value:status; coverage; number of contigs

Definition:For cases where annotation was provided by a community jamboree or model organism database rather than by a specific submitter
Structured comment name:annot_source
Section:sequencing
Expected value:annotation source description
